        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> That said, the tests will start to drift from the reality of the defaults.\r\n\r\nCosmetic defaults do not have any meaningful impact on the test's notion of reality. If they did, that's an architecture bug because it means we lack coverage for all the users that choose non-default settings.\r\n\r\nOf course, it's preferable to avoid differences if the churn cost is small. But a 5k churn cost is not small, and it is a real cost if we decide to change the default again later.\r\n\r\n>  I put it through AI to sort through it a bit more, and it came back with this:\r\n\r\nIt's fine if a few tests need to set local overrides. `n.clear{}` has `args_rm` for cases where the default `nvim_set` is doing unwanted things.",
